Introduction¶

I am going to explore NICS Firearm data, The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level

Here are some interesting questions which need no be addressed

  1. In General. What is the distribution of gun registrations over the years?
  2. In General. What is the distribution of gun registrations over the Monthes?
  3. Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?
  4. What is the overall trend of gun Registrations?
  5. What is the Top 10 States in Gun Registration?
  6. What is the overall trend of gun Registrations per Top 10 States?

    Considering census and the association with gun registrations

    • for 2012 Data, what is the relation between gun registration and the number of firms?
    • What census data is most associated with high gun per State?

In [15]:
def clean_census(dataframe:pd.DataFrame): 
    dataframe = dataframe.transpose().reset_index() 
    dataframe.columns = dataframe.iloc[0] # use the first row as a Header
    dataframe.drop(0, inplace=True) # Dropping the first Row 
    dataframe.rename(columns={'Fact':'state'}, inplace=True) # change Column name from fact to State
    dataframe.rename(columns=(lambda x: x.strip().replace(" ","_").lower()), inplace=True) # Cleaning the header name 
    for name in dataframe.columns[1:]: 
        dataframe[name] = dataframe[name].astype(float) # Change all column Data type to Float
    return dataframe

def plot_growth(merged_data, states_data, states, method): # Function for plotting Growth related figures for the entire section 
    sns.set_style('white')
    # General look over the combined growth rate calculation with The States Rank to make sure that we are getting the right conclusion 
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(25,10)) 

    color = 'blue'
    ax[0].set_xlabel('Top 10 States',fontsize=25)
    ax[0].set_ylabel('Growth Rate', color=color, fontsize=25)
    ax[0].bar(merged_data['state'], merged_data['growth'],0.25, color='blue')
    ax[0].tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)
    ax[0].tick_params(axis='x', labelcolor='black', rotation=70)
    ax[0].set_title(f"Top 10 States by {method} Growth Rate",fontsize=25)

    ax2 = ax[0].twinx()  # instantiate a second axes that shares the same x-axis
    ax2.grid(True) 

    color = 'red'
    ax2.set_ylabel('State Rank', color=color, fontsize=25)  # we already handled the x-label with ax1
    ax2.plot(merged_data['state'], merged_data['rank'], color=color, marker="o", linestyle="--")
    ax2.set(yticks= merged_data['rank'], ylim=[60,1])
    ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)

    # General look over the combined growth rate calculation with The State Gun registration per year, just a closer look to see how it became the first state in growth rate  
    first_state = states_data[states_data['state'] == merged_data['state'][0]] # first State Related data 
    color = 'blue'
    ax[1].bar(first_state.year, first_state.total_reg, color=color)
    ax[1].set_xticks(first_state.year)
    ax[1].tick_params(axis='x', labelcolor='black', rotation=70)
    ax[1].set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=25)
    ax[1].set_ylabel('Growth Rate' , fontsize=25, color=color)
    ax[1].set_title(f"General View Over Gun Registrations per Year for {merged_data['state'][0]}", fontsize=25);

    ax3 = ax[1].twinx()  # instantiate a second axes that shares the same x-axis
    ax3.grid(True)
    first_s_gro = states[states['state'] == merged_data['state'][0]]
    color = 'red'
    ax3.set_ylabel('State Growth Rate', color=color, fontsize=25)  # we already handled the x-label with ax1
    ax3.plot(first_s_gro['year'], first_s_gro['growth'], color=color, marker="o", linestyle="--")
    ax3.set(yticks= first_s_gro['growth'])
    ax3.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)


    plt.tight_layout()

def plot_census(dataframe, year):
    x = np.array(dataframe['total_reg']) # X axis Values 
    y = np.array(dataframe['population_census'])# y axis Values 

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize= (20,10))

    # Plotting results 
    ax.scatter(x,y, color='blue')
    m, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)  # Calculating the linear regression
    ax.plot(x, (m*x + b), color='blue')
    #Plot label
    ax.set_xlabel(f'Total Gun Registrations In {year}', fontsize=15)
    ax.set_ylabel(f'Total Population census {year}', fontsize=25);
    ax.set_title(f'Relation between the Population census and total Gun registration for {year}', fontsize=20);

Conclusions¶

Before move to my conclusions there are some limitations related to data set, which need to be clear.

  • The Data represent the number of firearm background checks initiated through the NICS. They do not represent the number of firearms sold

  • there is not enough details about the admin and recheck permit criteria, which could be valuable if it was clear and consistent.

  • for Census Data, it not including the data over the years as gun data set, so I have built my conclusions on the available data only

  • for Census Data, it not including the data of all the States, so I have built my conclusions on the available data only

  • for Census Data, total firms dose not equal the total of the separate numbers in data set, so i was forced to exclude it

  • I could have built a relation module between total Income, employee percentage, and the criminal record percentage over the States if it was clearly defined

    Here are My Conclusions¶

    • In Average there is an increase in Gun registrations over the years.
    • 1999 has the highest growth rate ever, and 2012 has the highest growth rate since 2000 till 2017, and 2017 has the lowest growth rate
    • As a Month, "December" has the highest gun registrations rate
    • In General there is a tendency to Have a long gun then a hand gun, but very few for other types
    • The Top 10 Satates in Gun Registrations are "'Texas', 'California', 'Pennsylvania', 'Florida', 'Ohio', 'Tennessee','Virginia', 'Missouri', 'Colorado' and 'Alabama'"
    • Considering Top 10 States, for Florida, Ohio, Virginia and Tennessee, they tending to have a Hand Gun, unlike the general Trend
    • Generaly "Guam" has the highest growth rate, but it has a very small Registrations rate 51/55, which will make the growth rate get high by any small change.
    • As one in the top half Gun registrations rank, "Indiana" has the Highest Growth Rate in Average
    • For 2012 Census Data, generally there is a positive correlation between the Number of firms per State and Gun Registration
    • For 2016 and 2010 Census Data, we have found that generally there is a high association between population census and gun registration
    • There is a slightly negative correlation between the percentage for those how are 65 years old or above and the general gun registration
